<div class="post"><div class="posttop"><div class="username">Charbok</div><div class="date">April 21st, 2012, 01:38 PM</div></div><div class="posttext">Declare bankruptcy, that is.<br />
<br />
At least, that's quickly becoming my only real option at this point.<br />
<br />
History behind this statement.  Was married three years ago.  Due to some difference of opinions, we were forced to split up and dissolve the marriage.  I moved out, she kept the house. Within weeks it became apparent that she was unable to keep up with the house payments.<br />
<br />
The housing market was in it's first stages of collapsing, so you can see where this is going.  She managed to sell the house, but at a $30K loss.  We had an 80/20 loan and managed to fully pay the primary lender, but the secondary wouldn't agree to release her from the debt.  They did, however, unsecure the loan from the house.  A few months later, she declares bankruptcy.  I hear nothing more about it; not from her, not from the lender.  Nobody tries to contact me.<br />
<br />
Flash forward to today.  I've been saving for a few years now and have managed to put away a sizable amount to purchase my own home.  Something modest and affordable on my single man's income.  However, it seems no lender will talk to me.  Mainly because nowhere during the divorce proceedings nor during the sale of the house was my name struck from the loan.  <br />
<br />
I'll be the first to admit that it's partially my fault.  I should have thought of it early, I should have fought to get my name removed from the loan if she was keeping the house, and I should have consulted a financial adviser.  I really can't blame anything else, other than perhaps I wasn't thinking straight at the time and just wanted to move on with my life after being dumped by someone I thought I knew and trusted.  Doesn't change the fact that I'm sorely pissed off at the situation.  <br />
<br />
The problem now is that I'm responsible for 30 thousand dollars of debt that I simply cannot pay.  Maybe the creditor will take a settlement.  I have to fill out some hardship package which delves into every financial facet of my life and tears it apart.  Best case scenario, even if they'll take a settlement, is that my entire savings is wiped out and I start over.  Worst case is that I spend a few years paying on something I no longer own.  <br />
<br />
I figure if I'm letting some stranger access all my bank accounts and personal history, I might as well make it my lawyer and tell the creditor they're getting nothing.  I have student loans that would love to see my savings.  I can either settle and spend two years rebuilding my money, or declare and spend two years repairing my credit.  Seems about equal to me, except latter has the bonus of paying off student debt.<br />
<br />
The most excellent part?  I still get to talk to the ex-wife a few times a week, as we have kids.  Her version of an apology for this was - &quot;Oh, I'm sorry.  Hey, can you pick up the kids early?  I have an appointment with my marriage counselor.&quot;<br />
<br />
Astute readers my not a distinct lack of curse words.  I apologize for that.  I offer you a consolation 'fuck'.</div></div><hr />


